properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Avoca River.

  • A deepening low pressure trough and cold front will cross Victoria on Wednesday and track eastwards, bringing heavy showers and thunderstorms to the northern part of the state.
  • Catchments across central and northeastern Victoria are average to wet, and catchments across the northwest are relatively dry.
  • Widespread rainfall totals of 30 to 40mm are expected in the flood watch area from overnight Wednesday into Thursday, with isolated heavier falls of 70 to 100mm possible with thunderstorms and in areas with higher terrain. Showers and thunderstorms are forecast to ease into Friday.
  • River level rises are likely in catchments within the flood watch area, where minor flooding may develop from overnight Wednesday into Thursday. Isolated moderate flooding is also possible in areas with the heaviest rainfall.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may become flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/06/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
